'''''Eine warme Kartoffel ist ein warmes Bett''''' (''A Warm Potato is a Warm Bed'') is a collection of [[essay]]s by [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]]-winning author [[Herta Müller]], first published in 1992.<ref name="Eke 2017">{{cite book |last=Eke |first=N.O. |title=Herta Müller-Handbuch |publisher=J.B. Metzler |year=2017 |isbn=978-3-476-05401-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ujIyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA83 |language=de |access-date=25 July 2018 |page=59}}</ref> The essays were previously published as columns in the monthly Swiss publication ''Du'' between 1990 and 1992.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eine warme Kartoffel ist ein warmes Bett |url=https://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/3063077 |website=SearchWorks |publisher=Stanford Libraries |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Rock |first1=David |last2=Wolff |first2=Stefan |title=Coming Home to Germany?: The Integration of Ethnic Germans from Central and Eastern Europe in the Federal Republic |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9HEo46hyiMC&pg=PA186 |year=2002 |publisher=Berghahn Books |isbn=978-1-57181-729-7 |page=186}}</ref>

The title comes from one of the cryptic phrases that Müller's mother used in discussing the [[gulag]]s of the [[Socialist Republic of Romania]]. The title essay, written in 1991, was later expanded into a 304-page prose poem called ''Atemschaukel'' (''[[The Hunger Angel]]'').<ref>{{cite book |last1=Haines |first1=Brigid |last2=Marven |first2=Lyn |title=Herta Müller |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YstoAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124 |accessdate=23 July 2018 |date=20 June 2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-166959-0 |page=124–126}}</ref>

