{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Harka Gurung | native_name = Thula | native_name_lang = | image = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 5 January 1939 | birth_place = [[Taranche]], [[Lamjung]], Nepal | disappeared_date = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) --> | disappeared_place = | disappeared_status = | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2006|09|23|1939|01|05}} | death_place = [[Gunsha]], [[Taplejung]], Nepal | death_cause = [[2006 Shree Air Mil Mi-8 crash|Shree Air helicopter crash]] | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = Kathmandu | nationality = Nepali | other_names = | citizenship = Nepali | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Patna College, Patna]] | occupation = | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = Geographer, [[Urban planner|Planner]], [[Anthropologist]], author, artist, politician | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | salary = | net_worth = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | height = <!-- {{height|m=}} --> | weight = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} --> | television = | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | movement = | opponents = | boards = | criminal_charge = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources --> | criminal_penalty = | criminal_status = | spouse = | partner = <!-- unmarried life partner; use ''Name (1950–present)'' --> | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | module = | module2 = | module3 = | module4 = | module5 = | module6 = | website = <!-- {https://www.facebook.com/Drharkagurung?ref=br_tf}} --> | footnotes = | box_width = }}
'''Dr. Harka Bahadur Gurung''' (1939–2006) was a Nepalese geographer, anthropologist, author, artist and politician, known for his conservation work.<ref name=IPS>{{cite web|last=Pradhan|first=Suman|title=Chopper Tragedy Blow to Nature Conservation|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2006/09/nepal-chopper-tragedy-blow-to-nature-conservation/|publisher=Inter Press Service|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=CNAS>{{cite journal|last=Dahal|first=Dilli R.|title=In Memory of Dr Harka Gurung|journal=Contributions to Nepalese Studies|date=January 2007|volume=31|issue=1|pages=1–10|url=http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/contributions/pdf/CNAS_34_01_01.pdf|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>
==Early life== Gurung was born in [[Lamjung District|Lamjung]] on 5 February 1939, in the village of Taranche. His father was an [[Non-commissioned officer|NCO]] in the British Army. After completing his secondary education at King George Military School, he studied for a B.A. and M.A. in Geography at [[Patna University]], and later received a PhD from [[Edinburgh University]] after being offered a scholarship there.<ref name="CNAS"/>
==Academic career== After completing his PhD, Gurung worked as a Research Fellow at the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] in London, returning to Nepal in 1966 to take up a lecturing post at [[Tribhuvan University]] in Kathmandu. In 1984 he was appointed Visiting Fellow at the [[East–West Center]] in Hawaii. A prolific scholarly author, Gurung published fifteen books and around 675 academic articles and reports.<ref name="CNAS"/> He also worked as an advisor to the [[World Wildlife Fund]] in Nepal.<ref name="Thapa2009">{{cite book|author=Manjushree Thapa|title=A Boy from Siklis: The Life and Times of Chandra Gurung|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l4Qs8M5BOEIC&pg=PA189|accessdate=12 March 2013|date=8 September 2009|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-306548-7}}</ref>
==Political career== In 1968 Gurung was appointed Vice-Chairman of Nepal's National Planning Commission. He subsequently held several government posts, including Minister of State for Education, Trade and Industry Minister, and Minister of State for Tourism. He served as Director of the Asia and Pacific Development Centre from 1993–1998, and was a consultant for the [[World Bank]].<ref name="CNAS"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Nepal labours in the face of trade siege|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DKJUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hJADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6796,2678806&dq=harka-gurung&hl=en|accessdate=12 March 2013|newspaper=New Straits Times|date=11 April 1989}}</ref>
==Death== Gurung unfortunately died in 2006 along with 23 others in a [[2006 Shree Air Mil Mi-8 crash|helicopter crash]] at Ghunsa in [[Taplejung]], whilst returning from a conservation meeting.<ref name="IPS"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Former city student dies in Nepal copter crash|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/former-city-student-dies-in-nepal-copter-crash-1-999924|accessdate=12 March 2013|newspaper=The Scotsman|date=26 September 2006}}</ref> The 2011 Kathmandu International Mountain Film Festival was dedicated to his memory,<ref>{{cite web|last=Basnet|first=Rosha|title=Remote Lives at the 'KIMFF'|url=http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?no=334976&rel_no=1|work=Oh My News|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> and Lamjung F.C. created a memorial [[association football|football]] tournament in his honour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lamjung FC to organize football tournament in memory of Dr Harka Gurung|url=http://www.nepalifootball.com/l-news/nehru-cup-2012/203-lamjung-fc-to-organize-football-tournament-in-memory-of-dr-harka-gurung.html|work=Nepali Football.com|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> In Pokhara, a three-hectare eco-park (the Dr Harka, Chandra & Migma Memorial Laligurans Eco Park) was set up to commemorate Harka and those who died with him in the crash.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dhumpus to get an 'eco park'|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2369139171.html|work=The Kathmandu Post|publisher=HighBeam Research (subscription required)|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>
