{{History of the Philippines}}
The '''history of Luzon''' covers events that happened in the largest island of the Philippine Archipelago, [[Luzon]]. Luzon wrested the record of having the oldest man ever discovered in the Philippines with discovery of the [[Callao Man]] in 2007, which predated the [[Tabon Man]] by around 20,000 years.<ref name=morella>Morella, Cecil. (August 3, 2010). [http://news.discovery.com/archaeology/callao-man-philippines.html 'Callao Man' Could Redraw Filipino History]. Agence France-Presse. Retrieved October 21, 2010 from Discovery News.</ref> The written history of Luzon began in around 900 AD with the discovery of the [[Laguna Copperplate Inscription]] in 1989. After that, Luzon began to appear in the annals of the Chinese and Japanese. One example would be the [[Ming Shilu]], wherein Luzon appeared in 22 records.<ref name=wade>{{cite web|last=Wade|first=Geoff|title=Southeast Asia in the Ming Shi-lu: an open access resource, Luzon search|url=http://epress.nus.edu.sg/msl/search/?q=Luzon&b=Search|publisher=Asia Research Institute and the Singapore E-Press, National University of Singapore|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> Luzon was split among [[Hinduism|Hindu]]-[[Buddhism|Buddhist]] kingdoms, Muslim principalities, and [[Philippine mythology|ethnoreligious]] tribes, who had trading connections with [[Borneo]], [[Malay Peninsula|Malaya]], [[Java]], [[Indochina]], [[India]], [[Ryukyu Islands|Okinawa]], [[Japan]] and [[China]] before the Spanish established their rule. As a result of the [[Spanish–American War]], Luzon became American territory. In the [[Second World War]], Luzon saw one of the fiercest battles during the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines|Japanese occupation]]. Luzon, apart from being the largest island, had been the economic and political center of the Philippines ever since the country entered the Western Calendar, being home to the country's capital city, [[Manila]], and the country's largest [[metropolis]], [[Metro Manila]].

==Prehistory of Luzon==
{{Pre-hispanic History of the Philippines}}
{{further|Prehistory of the Philippines}}
[[File:Ph locator map luzon.png|thumb|left|Map showing [[Luzon]] in red shade.]]

The first evidence of the systematic use of Stone-Age technologies in the Philippines is estimated to have dated back to about 50,000 BC,<ref name="Jocano 2001 108">{{Harvnb|Jocano|2001|p=108}}</ref> and this phase in the development of proto-Philippine societies is considered to end with the rise of metal tools in about 500 BC, although stone tools continued to be used past that date.<ref>{{Harvnb|Jocano|2001|p=120}}</ref> However, new discoveries in Luzon, particularly in [[Rizal, Kalinga|Liwan, Kalinga]], found stone tools that were dated through potassium argon test at most 920,000 years old, and at least 750,000 years old.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ocampo|first=Ambeth|title=Looking Back 6: Prehistoric Philippines|year=2012|publisher=Anvil Publishing, Inc.|location=Mandaluyong City, Philippines|isbn=978-971-27-2767-2|pages=}}</ref>

The earliest human remains known in the Philippines are the fossilized remains discovered in 2007 by Armand Salvador Mijares in [[Callao Cave]], [[Peñablanca, Cagayan]]. The find was of a 67,000-year-old remains that predate the [[Tabon Man]], which was discovered in 1962 by [[Robert Bradford Fox]].<ref name=Scott1984pp14-15>{{Harvnb|Scott|1984|pp=14–15}}.</ref> Specifically, the find consisted of a single 61 millimeter [[metatarsal]] which, when dated using [[Radiometric dating#Modern dating methods|uranium series ablation]], was found to be at least about 67,000 years old.<ref name=morella/> If definitively proven to be remains of [[Homo sapiens]], since there was a certainty that the Callao Man could be a [[Homo floresiensis]], it would antedate the 47,000-year-old remains of [[Tabon Man]] to become the earliest human remains known in the Philippines, and one of the oldest human remains in the Asia Pacific.<ref>Severino, Howie G. (August 1, 2010). [http://www8.gmanews.tv/story/197541/researchers-discover-fossil-of-human-older-than-tabon-man Researchers discover fossil of human older than Tabon Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100804040818/http://www.gmanews.tv/story/197541/researchers-discover-fossil-of-human-older-than-tabon-man |date=2010-08-04 }}. [[GMA News]]. Retrieved October 21, 2010.</ref><ref>"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/philippines/7924538/Archaeologists-unearth-67000-year-old-human-bone-in-Philippines.html Archaeologists unearth 67,000-year-old human bone in Philippines]". ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.</ref>

The primary theory surrounding the migration of Callao Man and his contemporaries to Luzon from what is believed to be the present-day Indonesia is that they came by raft. It is notable that the approximate time this happened is, according to experts, prior to the point when human beings were thought to be capable of making long voyages across the sea. It has also been noted that Callao Man could have crossed into the Philippines by a [[land bridge]]. This is because at the time Callao Man lived, it was the period known as [[Ice age]] and the [[sea level]] was lower. Because of lower sea levels, there could have been an [[Isthmus]] between the Philippines and the rest of [[Southeast Asia]].<ref>"[http://opinion.inquirer.net/inquireropinion/columns/view/20100702-278657/Callao-Man Callao Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723154949/http://opinion.inquirer.net/inquireropinion/columns/view/20100702-278657/Callao-Man |date=2011-07-23 }}". ''[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]''.</ref>

===Cultural and technological achievements in Luzon===
{{further|Cultural achievements of pre-colonial Philippines}}
Mining in the Philippines began around 1000 BC. However, the discovery of a [[brass]] needle in Musang Cave, Cagayan pushed back the date to 2160 BC, the date the needle was made.<ref name=tan>{{cite book|last=Tan|first=Samuel|title=A History of the Philippines|year=1987|publisher=University of the Philippines|location=Quezon City}}</ref> Metal smiths from this era had already developed a crude version of modern metallurgical processes, notably the hardening of soft iron through [[carburization]]. However, unlike the typical pattern, there had been no shift to copper or bronze implements before iron implements, it had been from stone to iron.<ref>{{Harvnb|Dizon|1983|p=28}}</ref>

==History of Luzon during the Classical Period==
{{further|History of the Philippines (900–1521)}}

===Luzon in early world maps===
[[File:Ptolemy-World Vat Urb 82.jpg|right|thumb|Ptolemy's 1st projection, redrawn under [[Maximus Planudes]] around 1300]]
{{further|Early world maps}}
[[Greek people|Greeks]] may have reached the Visayan Islands around AD&nbsp;21<ref>[http://cebu-online.com/swum/html/exhibits.html Cebu, a Port City in Prehistoric and in Present Times]. Accessed September 05, 2008, citing {{Harvnb|Regalado|Franco|1973|p=78}}</ref> and some scholars{{who|date=March 2015}} conflate accounts of the Golden Island ([[Sumatra]]) and [[Golden Chersonese]] ([[Malay Peninsula|Malaysia]]) by classical writers such as [[Josephus]], [[Pomponius Mela]], and [[Ptolemy's Geography|Ptolemy]] with locations in the Philippines.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} Gold jewelry of Philippine origin has been found in 1st-century [[Roman Egypt|Egypt]].<ref>Legeza, Laszlo. "Tantric Elements in pre-Hispanic Philippines Gold Art," Arts of Asia, July–Aug. 1988, pp.129–136.</ref><ref>Peralta, J.T. "Prehistoric gold ornaments from the Central Bank of the Philippines," Arts of Asia 1981, no.4, p.54.
</ref><ref>Villegas, Ramon N. ''Ginto: History Wrought in Gold'', Manila: Bangko Central ng Pilipinas, 2004.</ref>{{dubious|date=March 2015}}{{Verify source|date=March 2015}}

===Laguna Copperplate Inscription===
{{main|Laguna Copperplate Inscription}}
[[File:Laguna Copperplate Inscription.gif|right|thumb|The Laguna Copperplate Inscription (circa AD 900) is inscribed with small writing hammered into its surface. It shows heavy [[Greater India|Indian cultural influence]] (by way of [[Srivijaya]]) present in the Philippines prior to Spanish colonization in the 16th century.]]

The Laguna Copperplate Inscription is the earliest known written document found in the [[Philippines]]. The plate was found in 1989 by a sand labourer near the mouth of the Lumbang River in [[Barangay]] Wawa, [[Lumban, Laguna|Lumban]], [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]]. The inscription on the plate was first deciphered by [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[anthropologist]] [[Antoon Postma]].<ref>(2010-05-07). [http://www.allphilippines.com/?p=771 "Laguna Copperplate Inscription"]. All Philippines. Retrieved on 2011-11-17.</ref><ref>Tiongson, Jaime F. (2010-08-08). [http://www.bayangpinagpala.org/ "Laguna Copperplate Inscription: A New Interpretation Using Early Tagalog Dictionaries"]. Bayang Pinagpala. Retrieved on 2011-11-18.</ref>

The inscription is on a thin copper plate measuring less than 20 × 30&nbsp;cm (8 × 12 inches) in size with words directly embossed onto the plate. It differs in manufacture from other Javanese scrolls of the period, which had the words inscribed onto a heated, softened scroll of metal.<ref name="mts" />

Inscribed on it the [[Saka era]] date year of Saka 822, month of Waisaka, the fourth day of the waning moon, which corresponds to Monday, 21 April 900 AD in the [[Gregorian calendar]].<ref name="bibingka" /> The writing system used is the [[Old Kawi|Kawi Script]], while the language is a variety of [[Old Malay]], and contains numerous loanwords from [[Sanskrit]] and a few non-Malay vocabulary elements whose origin is between [[Tagalog language|Old Tagalog]] and [[Old Javanese]].<ref>Postma, Antoon. (1992). The Laguna Copper-Plate Inscription: Text and Commentary. ''Philippine Studies'' vol. 40, no. 2:183–203</ref> The document states that it releases its bearers, the children of ''Namwaran'', from a debt in [[gold]] amounting to 1 ''kati'' and 8 ''suwarnas'' (865&nbsp;grams).<ref name="mts">Morrow, Paul (2006-07-14). [http://www.mts.net/~pmorrow/lcieng.htm "Laguna Copperplate Inscription"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205031106/http://www.mts.net/~pmorrow/lcieng.htm |date=2008-02-05 }}. Sarisari etc.</ref><ref name="bibingka">[http://www.bibingka.com/dahon/lci/lci.htm#lci_graphics "The Laguna Copperplate Inscription] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121194304/http://bibingka.com/dahon/lci/lci.htm |date=2014-11-21 }}. Accessed September 04, 2008.</ref> The original text was written with an English translation below. (''Place names are in bold.'')

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
'''Transliteration'''
{{col-break}}
'''English translation'''
{{col-end}}

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
Swasti. Ṣaka warṣatita 822 [[Vaisakha|Waisakha]] masa di(ng) [[Jyotisha|Jyotiṣa]].
{{col-break}}
''Long Live! In the Year of Saka 822, month of [[Vaisakha|Waisakha]], according to the [[Hindu calendar|astronomer]].''
{{col-end}}

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
[[Chaturthi|Caturthi]] [[Hindu calendar#Day|Kriṣnapaksa]] [[Hindu calendar#Day|Somawāra]] sana tatkala Dayang Angkatan lawan dengan nya sānak barngaran si Bukah anak da dang Hwan Namwaran di bari waradāna wi shuddhapattra ulih sang pamegat senāpati di [[Tondo, Manila|Tundun]] barja(di) dang Hwan Nāyaka tuhan [[Pila, Laguna|Pailah]] Jayadewa.
{{col-break}}
''The fourth day of the waning moon, Monday. On this occasion, Lady Angkatan, and her relative whose name is Bukah, the children of the Honorable Namwaran, were awarded a document of complete pardon from the Commander-in-Chief of '''[[Tondo, Manila|Tundun]]''', represented by the Lord Minister of '''[[Pila, Laguna|Pailah]]''', Jayadewa.''
{{col-end}}

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
Di krama dang Hwan Namwaran dengan dang kayastha shuddha nu di parlappas hutang da walenda Kati 1 Suwarna 8 di hadapan dang Huwan Nayaka tuhan [[Pulilan|Puliran]] Kasumuran dang Hwan Nayaka tuhan [[Pila, Laguna|Pailah]] barjadi ganashakti.
{{col-break}}
''This means that, through the Honorable Scribe, the Honourable Namwaran is totally cleared of his salary-related debts of 1 ''Katî'' and 8 ''Suwarna'', before the Honorable Lord Minister of '''[[Pulilan|Puliran]]''', Kasumuran; by the authority of the Lord Minister of '''[[Pila, Laguna|Pailah]]''', represented by Ganasakti.''
{{col-end}}

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
Dang Hwan Nayaka tuhan Binwangan barjadi bishruta tathapi sadana sanak kapawaris ulih sang pamegat [[Bali|Dewata]] [ba]rjadi sang pamegat [[Kingdom of Medang|Mdang]] dari bhaktinda diparhulun sang pamegat.
{{col-break}}
''the Honourable and widely-renowned Lord Minister of '''[[Binangonan, Rizal|Binwagan]]''', represented by Bisruta. And, with his whole family, upon ordered of the Lord Minister of '''[[Bali|Dewata]]''', represented by the Chief of '''[[Medang Kingdom|Mdang]]''', because of his loyalty as a subject of the Commander-in-Chief.''
{{col-end}}

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
Ya makanya sadanya anak cucu dang Hwan Namwaran shuddha ya kapawaris dihutang da dang Hwan Namwaran di sang pamegat [[Bali|Dewata]].''
{{col-break}}
''Therefore, the living descendants of the Honorable Namwaran are cleared of all debts of the Honorable Namwaran to the Lord Minister of '''[[Bali|Dewata]]'''.''
{{col-end}}

{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
Ini gerang syat syapanta ha pashkat ding ari kamudyan ada gerang urang barujara welung lappas hutang da dang Hwa
{{col-break}}
''This, in any case, whosoever, sometime in the future, who shall state that the debt is not yet cleared of the Honorable...''<ref>{{cite book|last=Ocampo|first=Ambeth|title=Looking Back 6: Prehistoric Philippines|year=2012|publisher=Anvil Publishing, Inc.|location=Mandaluyong City, Philippines|isbn=978-971-27-2767-2|pages=51–56}}</ref>
{{col-end}}

The Laguna Copperplate Inscription, among other recent finds such as the [[Golden Tara]] of [[Butuan]] and 14th century pottery and gold jewellery in [[Cebu]], is significant in revising [[History of the Philippines (900–1521)|precolonial Philippine history]], which was until then considered by some Western historians to be culturally isolated from the rest of Asia, as no evident pre-Hispanic written records were found at the time. Noted Philippine historian [[William Henry Scott (historian)|William Henry Scott]] debunked these theories in 1968 with his ''Prehispanic Source materials for the Study of Philippine History'' which was subsequently published in 1984.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Henry Scott |title=Prehispanic Source materials for the Study of Philippine History |isbn=971-10-0226-4}}</ref>

===The Barangay government===
{{further|Ancient barangay}}
[[File:Naturales 4.png|thumb|[[Tagalog people|Tagalog]] royalty and his wife, wearing the distinctive color of his class (red), an illustration from the [[Boxer Codex]].]]

The barangay government emerged in around 200 AD, which owed the name from the Malay boat [[balangay]]. In more developed barangays in the [[Visayas]] (e.g. [[Cebu]], [[Bohol]], and [[Panay]]) which were the first to be conquered by Spain by means of pacts, peace treaties, and reciprocal alliances,<ref>Cf. William Henry Scott, ''Cracks in the Parchment Curtain'', Quezon City: 1998, p. 4. Also cf. Antonio Morga, Sucessos de las Islas Filipinas, 2nd ed., Paris: 1890, p. xxxiii.</ref> the ''[[datu]]'' was at the top of the social order in a ''sakop'' or ''haop'' (elsewhere referred to as ''[[barangay]]'').<ref>William Henry Scott, ''Cracks in the Parchment Curtain'', Quezon City: 1998, pp. 102 and 112</ref> In Luzon, the social structure had been less stable and more complex as compared to the barangays in the Visayas. Enjoying a more extensive commerce than those in Visayas, having the influence of Bornean political contacts, and engaging in farming wet rice for a living, the Tagalogs, who had established the dominant pre-colonial barangays in Luzon, were described by the Spanish Augustinian friar [[Martin de Rada]] as more traders than warriors.<ref>Cf. William Henry Scott, ''Cracks in the Parchment Curtain'', Quezon City: 1998, pp. 124–125.</ref>

The more complex social structure of the Luzon barangays was less stable because it was still in a process of differentiating. A Jesuit priest Francisco Colin made an attempt to give an approximate comparison of it with the Visayan social structure in the middle of the 17th century. The term ''[[datu]]'' or ''[[lakan]]'', or ''apo'' refers to the chief, but the noble class to which the ''datu'' belonged to was known as the ''[[maginoo]]'' class. Any male member of the ''maginoo'' class can become a ''datu'' by personal achievement.<ref name="Scott125">Cf. William Henry Scott, Cracks in the Parchment Curtain, Quezon City: 1998, p. 125.</ref>

The [[Yongle Emperor]] instituted a Chinese Governor on Luzon during [[Zheng He]]'s [[Treasure voyages|voyages]] and appointed Ko Ch'a-lao to that position in 1405.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=EwnzBiM0LmAC&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=governor+chinese+luzon&source=bl&ots=f_OKEDJzJx&sig=AOflx3b7gvuXAVi9FwpwEkagXGg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=h653UM3JOqWD0QGhsoCIAg&ved=0CFsQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=governor%20chinese%20luzon&f=false Ho 2009], p. 33.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VbwogbQ3l8UC&pg=PT84&lpg=PT84&dq=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&source=bl&ots=k1pPMnaJ00&sig=yqYSGbkmGywHL2lqLEoCJlszqRE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q7Z3UPe1H-yx0AGNpoFQ&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Yung%20lo%20governor%20luzon&f=false Karnow 2010,]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Lb8a7P_2InIC&pg=RA3-PA7-IA5&lpg=RA3-PA7-IA5&dq=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&source=bl&ots=ws9ZH0NZyj&sig=_LDthDchdlCjqJSXSldjoetIsDg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q7Z3UPe1H-yx0AGNpoFQ&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Yung%20lo%20governor%20luzon&f=false Antonio & Dallo & Imperial, & Samson & Soriano 2007], p. 113.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=IplyAAAAMAAJ&q=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&dq=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&source=bl&ots=Ia7FLxUIKx&sig=Ch6FbTELyxSAL6WtWphhFvmO5fk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q7Z3UPe1H-yx0AGNpoFQ&ved=0CEYQ6AEwAw Lucman 2000], p. 234.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ykgeAAAAMAAJ&q=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&dq=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&source=bl&ots=smTgQMKpRK&sig=i1D26YMqvHcp7U6EOA8GqqXl9d4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q7Z3UPe1H-yx0AGNpoFQ&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBA Philippines (Republic). Office of Cultural Affairs 1965], p. 14.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0A5wAAAAMAAJ&q=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&dq=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&source=bl&ots=rUbPGsONWJ&sig=MFV5001cmkDU3lCiHWpsK6nxrQs&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q7Z3UPe1H-yx0AGNpoFQ&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBQ Alip 1954], p. 278.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=pJYVAQAAIAAJ&q=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&dq=Yung+lo+governor+luzon&source=bl&ots=PkhSGzWZOd&sig=6mwFB8vpT7Jq59qFUMAIRzmoROU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q7Z3UPe1H-yx0AGNpoFQ&v