[[File:La Citadelle de Québec, vue du ciel.JPG|thumb|250px|The [[Citadelle of Quebec]] is a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site of Canada]],<ref name=CRHP /> and also forms part of the [[Ramparts of Quebec City|Fortifications of Québec National Historic Site of Canada]].<ref name=CRHP>{{CRHP|9524|Québec Citadel|16 September 2011}}</ref> The fortress is located within the "Historic District of [[Old Québec]]", which was designated a [[World Heritage Site]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historic District of Old Québec|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/300|work=World Heritage Convention|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref>]]This is a list of '''forts''' in [[New France]] built by the [[Ancien Régime in France|French government]] or French [[Chartered companies]] in what later became [[Canada]], [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]], and the [[United States]]. They range from large European-type [[citadel]]s like at Quebec City to tiny [[trading post|fur-trade posts]].<ref name="Chartrand2013b">{{cite book|author=Rene Chartrand|title=French Fortresses in North America 1535–1763: Quebec, Montreal, Louisbourg and New Orleans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihSrWOl-zsIC&pg=PA1736|year=2013|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-4728-0317-7}}</ref>
==Canada== The French forts in Canada were located west from Alberta to the [[Atlantic Ocean]] and as far north as [[James Bay]]. Built between the 1640s and the 1750s, a few were captured from rival [[British Empire|British]] fur trading companies like [[Hudson's Bay Company]]. The forts were located on waterways to provide transport of fur back east to [[Montreal]] or [[Quebec City]]. A few have survived or been re-built, but most are ruins or simply disappeared after abandonment.
